      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Phase II - Historic Inventory Database Version 2

Between 07/16/2002 and 09/22/2004, the content and structure of the "Inventory of Historic Sites" document was updated, revised, and reformatted.  In addition to supplying new content, the structure of the document was changed from an alphabetical ordering to an ordering by historical eras and cultural themes.  Most of the original landmark entries still existed, but many underwent name changes or content expansion.

The Historic Inventory database underwent a corresponding upgrade.  Fields were added to accomodate the Era/Theme hierarchy of the new document.  New entries were added and records updated, as appropriate.

The Inventory document contains entries for many types of historical entities.  It can also have single entries which contain a listing of individual locations.  Three types of spatial features were determined to describe entities within the Inventory document, Landmark Areas (Historic Districts, Parks, Cemeteries, etc.), Landmark Structures (Buildings, Memorials, Fountains, etc.), and Landmark Sites (Point Locations).

Overlap between spatial features was expected between Landmark Sites and Landmark Areas or Structures.  In addition, individual Landmark Sites or Areas might exist.  

Three GIS ID fields were used to link records in the Inventory Database to their corresponding spatial entity (Landmark Areas, Structures, or Sites).  These fields were added to the original Inventory table and to a Collections table that tracked individual locations within single Inventory document entries.</procdesc>

      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Phase III - Spatial Data Collection and Creation

The "Inventory of Historic Sites" document addresses a wide variety of features.  Using the current DCGIS historic spatial features as a guide (Historic Districts, Landmark Areas, Landmark Sites), DCOP staff began assembling related spatial data sources.

A simple attribution scheme was defined for the three spatial datasets (GIS_ID, NAME, ADDRESS, SSL).  Detailed attribution that mirrored the content of the Inventory document would be managed in the Inventory database and would be linked to the appropriate spatial dataset(s) by a unique GIS ID.

The assembled spatial data sources were stripped of attribution and replaced with the simple attribution scheme (GIS_ID, NAME, ADDRESS, SSL). The table below details the relationships between the GIS ID in the Inventory database to the individual spatial datasets.

  Landmark      Inventory     Format           Spatial            GIS Link
     Type               ID                                 Dataset

     Area            LND_ID     LND_0000    LandmarkPly      GIS_ID
 Structures       HSE_ID     HSE_0000    LandmarkBldg    GIS_ID
    Sites            SSL_ID      SSL_0000     LandmarkPt       GIS_ID


Assembled all data sources that had undergone attribute reduction and consistency into source Personal Geo-database.  Developed ArcMap MXD for updating component data sources including:

  Landmark Areas
    HistDisPly         Historic Districts           (DCOP)
    Reservations    DC Reservations         (DCOP)

    CemeteryPly     Cemeteries                   (DCGIS)
    LandmrkPly      Old Landmark Areas    (DCGIS)
    WaterPly          River Boundaries         (DCGIS)
    RoadPly           Road Boundaries         (DCGIS)

    ParkPly            NPS Parks                   (NPS)

  Landmark Structures
    BldgPly            Building Footprints        (DCGIS)

  Landmark Sites
    OwnerPt          Owner Points                (DCGIS)
    PlacesOfWorship  Churches                (DCGIS)

Concurrently walked through the Inventory Document, Inventory Database, and Spatial Data Locator (ArcMap).  Determined that each document entry has a spatial data equivalent.  Concurrently assign a unique GIS ID to Inventory Database and associated spatial dataset.  If no spatial data exists, designate "GIS Placeholder" within Inventory Document text.

In the event that a single Inventory Document entry references multiple spatial locations (collections), individual location records were created in a separate table.  GIS features were created and/or attributed, as appropriate.  Collection records included a link back to the original Record ID as well as simple descriptive information.

The location and visual validation of the Landmark Structures and Landmark Sites was facilitated by two tools developed by DC Office of Planning (DCOP) staff.  An address geocoder utility allowed GIS staff to zoom into a specific location (address) as defined in the Inventory record.  In addition, a Pictometry Viewing utility enebled staff to view a given location (structure) close enough for visual clues.  These two tools in conjunction with referencing to Historic American Building Survey (HABS) website found the majority of sites.</procdesc>

        <procdesc>Phase IV - Spatial Data Validation

Several fields were added to maintain consistency with the DCGIS spatial data model ([OBJECTID], [AID], [WEB_URL], and [UPDATE_DATE]).  Two additional fields ([LABEL] and [NR_ELIGIBLE]) were incorporated into the updated dataset. [LABEL] is used to indicate a feature's name on a display or map. [NR_ELIGIBLE] is a flags that indicates whether the feature is eligible for entry in the National Register list.

Historic Preservation staff performed a visual validation of the Landmark Structures dataset.  Structure locations were plotted and checked against known locations.  The Landmark Points was validated concurrently.

Those locations that were identifies as incorrect were highlighted for later corrections.  Landmark Collections were identified as a new means of grouping spatially-related features.</procdesc>

    <overview>
      <eaover>Several fields are standard with the DCGIS Spatial Data Model and have been incorporated into this dataset.  These are:

OBJECTID    Index Record Number
AID               Address ID for link to the Master Address Repository (MAR)
WEB_URL   Internet Link to Spatial Data Reference
UPDATE_DATE  Date of Most Recent Modification

Other fields are common to the three Landmark feature datasets (Landmark Areas, Landmark Structures, and Landmark Sites) which provide general descriptive information for the spatial data.  A GIS_ID field is also provided which links back to a comprehensive database that captures feature data identified in the Inventory of Historic Sites document.  The fields are:

  GIS_ID        Spatial Link ID
  NAME          Landmark Name
  LABEL         Landmark Name for Mapping or Display
  ADDRESS   Address Description
  SSL             Square-Suffix-Lot
  LIST_INFO  Identifies whether feature is a Registered Landmark ("Reg") 
                          or Informational / Contributing Feature ("Info")

The Landmark Structures / Landmark Sites dataset contains an additional field ([COLLECT_ID]) that indicates whether this feature is part of a larger collection.  The content of this field would be the GIS_ID of the Landmark Areas dataset ("LND_0000") in which this feature is contained.

Format of the GIS_ID field depends upon the Landmark feature dataset in use:

     Name                        Description                   GIS_ID
  LandmarkPly             Landmark Areas           LND_0000
  LandmarkBldg           Landmark Structures    HSE_0000
  LandmarkPt               Landmark Sites            SSL_0000
</eaover>
